data.content:
In xUnit, setup/teardown maps to constructors, `IDisposable`, and `IClassFixture<T>`:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class |

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Constructor/Dispose replace [SetUp] / [TearDown]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- **Per-test setup** → constructor (xUnit creates a new instance per test)
- **Per-test teardown** → `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **One-time setup/teardown** → extract into a fixture class implementing `IDisposable`, then use `IClassFixture<T>`
- `[Test]` → `[Fact]`, and `Assert.That(...)` → `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` etc.
